The article highlights the shared vision and partnership between Prime Minister Kishida Fumio of Japan, President Yoon Suk Yeol of the Republic of Korea (ROK), and President Joseph R. Biden, Jr. of the United States. The partnership is based on shared values, mutual respect, and a commitment to advancing prosperity in their countries, the region, and the globe. They pledge to uphold a free and open Indo-Pacific, oppose unilateral attempts to change the status quo by force, and promote peace and stability in the region. The leaders also express support for ASEAN centrality and unity, cooperation with Pacific Island countries, and the complete denuclearization of North Korea. They emphasize the importance of peace and stability in the Taiwan Strait and call for a peaceful resolution of cross-Strait issues. The leaders also commit to open and fair economic practices, technology cooperation, addressing climate change, and promoting development and humanitarian response cooperation. They underscore their commitment to upholding the principles of the UN Charter, non-proliferation, and the participation of women in society. The article concludes by stating that the trilateral partnership will be guided by these shared principles for years to come.